  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Maria Weston Chapman discusses Mary Weston&apos;s illness. She tells of Wendell Phillips&apos;s handling of Anne Warren Weston&apos;s affairs. She gives a long account of a tax controversy between Weymouth and Boston. Chapman distributed 25 tracts. She talks about the &quot;Mobocrats&quot; and [James] Redpath. She objects to yielding a &quot;hair&apos;s-breadth&quot; to the opposition. Discusses a conversation with Ann Terry Phillips about the advisability of giving advice to one&apos;s friends. Chapman talks about the usefulness of some of the recent anti-slavery meetings. She mentions the continuation of the John Brown meeting and refers again to Redpath.</subfield>
